# Reference Examples

## Glossary
**G1. Progressive Disclosure** [EN] – Reveals information incrementally to reduce cognitive load. Related: Cognitive Load  
**G2. Information Architecture** [EN] – Structural design of information environments. Related: Sitemap, Navigation  
**G3. Affordance** [EN] – Object property suggesting how to use it. Visual cues for interaction. Related: Signifier  
**G4. Cognitive Load** [EN] – Mental effort required to process information. Minimize to improve UX. Related: Progressive Disclosure  
**G5. Design Tokens** [EN] – Centralized design values (color, spacing, typography). Enables consistency. Related: Design System  
**G6. Atomic Design** [EN] – Hierarchical component system (atoms → molecules → organisms → templates). Related: Design System  
**G7. Heuristic Evaluation** [EN] – Usability inspection using Nielsen's 10 principles. Related: Usability Testing  
**G8. Card Sorting** [EN] – User groups content to inform IA. Open/closed variants. Related: Information Architecture  
**G9. System Usability Scale (SUS)** [EN] – 10-item questionnaire for perceived usability. Score 0-100. Related: Usability Metrics  
**G10. WCAG** [EN] – Web Content Accessibility Guidelines. POUR principles (Perceivable, Operable, Understandable, Robust). Related: Accessibility

## Tools
**T1. Figma** [EN] – Collaborative design platform. Components, prototyping, design systems. Updated: 2024-10. Freemium. https://figma.com  
**T2. Hotjar** [EN] – User behavior analytics. Heatmaps, recordings, surveys. Updated: 2024-09. Freemium. https://hotjar.com  
**T3. Optimal Workshop** [EN] – IA research tools. Card sorting, tree testing, first click. Updated: 2024-08. Paid. https://optimalworkshop.com  
**T4. Axe DevTools** [EN] – Accessibility testing. WCAG compliance, browser extension. Updated: 2024-10. Freemium. https://deque.com/axe  
**T5. Storybook** [EN] – Component documentation and testing. Isolated development. Updated: 2024-11. Free/OSS. https://storybook.js.org

## Literature
**L1. Norman, D. (2013). *The Design of Everyday Things* (Revised). Basic Books.** – Affordances, signifiers, conceptual models, human-centered design  
**L2. Krug, S. (2014). *Don't Make Me Think* (3rd). New Riders.** – Usability principles, web navigation, user testing  
**L3. Cooper, A., Reimann, R., & Cronin, D. (2014). *About Face: The Essentials of Interaction Design* (4th). Wiley.** – Goal-directed design, personas, interaction patterns  
**L4. Gothelf, J., & Seiden, J. (2021). *Lean UX* (3rd). O'Reilly.** – Collaborative design, hypothesis-driven development, MVP validation  
**L5. Knapp, J., Zeratsky, J., & Kowitz, B. (2016). *Sprint: How to Solve Big Problems*. Simon & Schuster.** – Design sprints, rapid prototyping, user validation  
**L6. Nielsen, J., & Loranger, H. (2006). *Prioritizing Web Usability*. New Riders.** – Usability heuristics, testing methods, best practices

